Is it any wonder Abu Ghraib was allowed to happen?  The left hand doesn't know what the right hand in the same cabinet is doing on intelligence issues.  When senior individuals in the same cabinet don't communicate or understand the issues, how can entire departments do it on similarly crucial issues?  Think about 9/11, and what the lack of all this cost everyone.  <br>
<br>
How smart is it, in anyone's opinion, to have a policy of pre-emptive war with such laughable leadership on intelligence matters?  Or mismanage the war in such a way as to increase terrorism, the number of terrorists and fail to undermine popular support for that terrorism?  I don't think events have ever been so badly managed since Vietnam- I don't think any career Senator from any party in any era would do a worse job.  <br>
<br>
Then look at Ahmed Chalabi, paid hundreds of thousands a month of taxpayer money by one branch of government and castigated by another branch.  There has never been such a veil of secrecy over an administration, nor such a level of incompetence or miscommunication without someone being fired.  What I find ironic is that those who were fired over their views have been proven right- from Army CoS Shinseki who said more troops would be needed (then getting fired by Rummy)- and then Paul O'Neill, both of them have been proven right.  <br>
<br>
That points to a critical lack of leadership and judgement.  Firing a general of 27 years loyal service for expressing a strategic opinion then retaining a Defence secretary who had no idea of the extent of prison abuses throughout his department in 2 theaters of war- I can't think of anything so obviously criminal in recent history.  Except perhaps, deliberately exposing a CIA operative over her husband's political views(Valerie Plame)- something most people should find treasonous and despicable.  Purely personally- I find tolerance of these things, and deep intolerance for a President having an extramarital affair that didn't hurt/kill anyone...a bloody ridiculous paradox.<br>
<br>
A question perhaps that is worth posing to those who support the administration unreservedly- how bad does it have to get before a change of leadership is a must?  It was too long for Vietnam, does there need to be that level of policy incompetence before a *single* administration official loses their job, never mind an election?  A war bereft of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cassus belli</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, an increase in terrorism worldwide as a result of that war, prisoner abuse and the near-complete failure of post-war policy not seen since the Crimean war.  That would be enough to unseat dictators, doesn't seem enough for democracy to do the same though :P<br>
<br>
Are people going to vote based on Bush's record, or based on their fears about John Kerry?  What I've read indicates the latter, likely due to campaign ads so full of misinformation, Hannity would be proud of them.  I support neither candidate or their policies as a whole, but I do know that it is rarely a good idea to vote based on fear of any kind.  Citizens living in fear are easily exploited, misled and ruled by commercial interests.  The political success of Hitler can be attributed in no small part to the fear of a weaker alternative that wouldn't revive the economy or restore Germany's glory.  Something that large special interest groups exploited to support Hitler's rise to power.  A lesson to remember at the ballot box perhaps Tiig?<br>
